levels.level_description: This level involves basic tasks and activities that are typically performed under close supervision. Individuals at this level are learning and building foundational skills.
At this level, individuals can perform tasks with some guidance and support. They contribute to team efforts and continue to develop their skills.
Individuals at this level can work independently and apply their skills to routine tasks and activities. They have a solid understanding of the subject matter.
This level involves more complex and specialized tasks. Individuals are capable of providing guidance and support to others and can handle non-routine situations.
At this level, individuals have a deep understanding of the domain and can ensure the quality of work. They may also provide advice and guidance to others.
Individuals at this level have a strategic perspective and can initiate projects, set strategies, and manage complex endeavors. They play a leadership role.

This is the highest level in SFIA, and it involves influencing and shaping the organization's direction and vision. Individuals at this level are senior leaders who can mobilize resources and drive significant change.

levels.full_description: At Level 1, individuals develop foundational skills that will later support strategic and planning capabilities. This begins with understanding basic business operations through day-to-day tasks, observing team interactions, and following established procedures while learning why they exist. They start developing information gathering skills by collecting and organizing basic data, taking clear notes, documenting work activities, and learning where to find relevant information. Time management is practiced through handling personal daily tasks, meeting assigned deadlines, using basic planning tools, and understanding priorities set by supervisors. Communication skills are built by clearly expressing task status, asking appropriate questions, writing clear emails, and contributing in team meetings. They also begin developing problem analysis capabilities by identifying basic issues in routine work, learning to break down simple problems, following troubleshooting guides, and understanding cause and effect in basic work scenarios. These fundamental skills, while not strategic in nature, form the essential building blocks that enable progression to more strategic roles at higher levels.
levels.brief_description: Develop foundational skills that will later support strategic and planning capabilities

levels.full_description: At Level 2, individuals begin taking more initiative while still working under routine direction. Their understanding of business operations expands to include recognizing process inefficiencies and suggesting simple improvements, while starting to make connections between different business areas and their interdependencies. Information gathering becomes more proactive, as they learn to anticipate what data might be needed and begin basic analysis of trends or patterns in their work area. Time management skills advance to include planning small projects or coordinating work with immediate colleagues, while starting to identify potential risks or bottlenecks in their work. Communication develops to include adapting their style for different audiences, preparing basic reports, and beginning to influence team decisions through well-reasoned suggestions. Their problem analysis capabilities grow to include investigating the root causes of issues, proposing potential solutions, and understanding the broader impact of problems beyond their immediate task. While still not operating at a strategic level, these individuals demonstrate greater autonomy and begin to show the analytical and collaborative skills that will later support strategic thinking and planning at higher levels.
levels.brief_description: Begin taking more initiative while still working under routine direction.

levels.full_description: At Level 3, individuals begin to exercise discrete judgment and initiative in making decisions that impact their area of work. Their business understanding deepens to include analyzing operational effectiveness and making recommendations for process improvements, while demonstrating awareness of how their decisions impact broader organizational goals. They take responsibility for planning and organizing substantial pieces of work, developing project approaches, and coordinating resources within their sphere of influence. Information gathering evolves into more sophisticated analysis, as they synthesize data from multiple sources to identify trends and opportunities, conduct basic cost-benefit analyses, and make evidence-based recommendations. Their time management expands to include creating and maintaining medium-term plans, managing competing priorities effectively, and helping others to plan and organize their work. Communication skills advance to include influencing stakeholders, preparing detailed reports and proposals, and facilitating productive discussions to achieve specific outcomes. Problem solving becomes more strategic as they evaluate alternative approaches, consider business implications, and implement solutions that address root causes rather than just symptoms. While not yet operating at an enterprise strategic level, these professionals demonstrate the analytical thinking, planning capabilities, and business acumen that form the foundation for higher-level strategic roles.
levels.brief_description: Exercise discrete judgment and initiative in making decisions that impact their area of work

levels.full_description: At Level 4, individuals take significant responsibility for planning and delivery within their specialist area, demonstrating leadership and strategic thinking that influences their broader department or function. Their business understanding encompasses detailed knowledge of their organization's objectives and market position, allowing them to guide decision-making that aligns with corporate strategy. They develop comprehensive plans that consider multiple scenarios and contingencies, while managing complex interdependencies across different teams or projects. Their analytical capabilities extend to evaluating market trends, assessing competitive landscapes, and identifying strategic opportunities within their domain. They take ownership of substantial resources and budgets, making informed decisions about resource allocation and investment priorities. Communication at this level involves negotiating with senior stakeholders, building consensus across different business areas, and articulating complex strategies in clear, actionable terms. They demonstrate sophisticated problem-solving abilities by addressing systemic issues, managing strategic risks, and developing innovative solutions that create lasting business value. These professionals actively contribute to departmental strategy, translate organizational objectives into practical implementation plans, and take accountability for delivering significant business outcomes. While their strategic influence may still be primarily within their specialist area or department, they show mature capability in balancing short-term operational needs with longer-term strategic objectives.
levels.brief_description: Take significant responsibility for planning and delivery within their specialist area

levels.full_description: Collates information and creates reports and insights to support strategy management processes. Ensures that all stakeholders are aware of the strategic management approach and timetables. Provides support and guidance to help stakeholders adhere to the approach. Develops and communicates plans to drive forward the strategy and related change planning. Contributes to the development of policies, standards and guidelines for strategy development and planning.
levels.brief_description: Operate with significant strategic influence, setting direction and shaping strategy across major business functions or enterprise-wide initiatives

levels.full_description: At Level 6, individuals operate at the highest levels of strategic leadership, setting vision and direction that shapes entire organizations or major business divisions. They demonstrate exceptional business acumen and foresight, making decisions that influence long-term organizational sustainability and market position. Their strategic planning encompasses developing enterprise-wide strategies that consider global market dynamics, emerging technologies, and complex stakeholder ecosystems. They exercise authority over substantial portions of organizational resources, making critical decisions about major investments, acquisitions, or strategic pivots that fundamentally impact the organization's future. Their analytical capabilities extend to understanding complex global economic trends, regulatory landscapes, and emerging business models, using this insight to position their organization for future success. Leadership at this level involves inspiring and guiding executive teams, shaping board-level discussions, and building strategic alliances across industry boundaries. They take ultimate accountability for major strategic initiatives, balancing short-term performance with long-term value creation while navigating significant ambiguity and risk. Their communication skills enable them to influence at board level, shape industry dialogue, and build consensus among diverse stakeholder groups with competing interests. Problem-solving at this level involves addressing challenges that impact entire industries or markets, requiring sophisticated understanding of geopolitical, social, and economic factors. These executives demonstrate the ability to reimagine business models, drive transformational change, and create lasting competitive advantage through strategic innovation.
levels.brief_description: Operate at the highest levels of strategic leadership, setting vision and direction that shapes entire organizations or major business divisions

levels.full_description: At Level 7, individuals function at the apex of strategic leadership, typically in roles that shape entire industries or major global organizations. They demonstrate exceptional vision and insight that extends beyond individual organizations to influence industry direction, regulatory frameworks, and market evolution. Their strategic planning encompasses multi-year, multi-market strategies that consider complex global ecosystems, societal trends, and emerging paradigms that may reshape entire industries. They exercise influence over enterprise-wide strategy and governance, making decisions that can impact thousands of employees and billions in resources across multiple global markets. Their analytical scope extends to understanding macroeconomic patterns, geopolitical dynamics, and technological disruption at a global scale, using this understanding to position organizations or industries for long-term success. Leadership at this level involves guiding boards, influencing government policy, and building coalitions across industry boundaries to drive systemic change. They take accountability for enterprise-wide strategy and governance, balancing shareholder value with broader societal impact while navigating unprecedented levels of complexity and uncertainty. Their communication capabilities enable them to shape public discourse, influence policy makers, and build alignment across diverse global stakeholder groups. Problem-solving at this level involves addressing challenges that impact multiple industries or entire economies, requiring sophisticated understanding of long-term societal, technological, and environmental trends. These leaders demonstrate the ability to envision and shape the future of their industries, drive systemic innovation, and create lasting impact on business and society.
levels.brief_description: Function at the apex of strategic leadership, typically in roles that shape entire industries or major global organizations
